Consider an electron in a 2D particle in a box, representing the π-electrons in a graphene-like fragment with dimensions L_x = 2 \, \text{nm} and L_y = 1 \, \text{nm}. Calculate the energy of the electron for the quantum numbers n_x = 1 and n_y = 2

Solution 6

The energy for a 2D particle in a box is given by:E_{n_x,n_y} = \frac{h^2}{8m} \left( \frac{n_x^2}{L_x^2} + \frac{n_y^2}{L_y^2} \right)

Using h = 6.626 \times 10^{-34}{J \cdot s} \,, m = 9.109 \times 10^{-31} \, \text{kg}, L_x = 2 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m}, and L_y = 1 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m}, we calculate:E_{1,2} = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34})^2}{8 \times 9.109 \times 10^{-31}}
\left( \frac{1^2}{(2 \times 10^{-9})^2} + \frac{2^2}{(1 \times 10^{-9})^2} \right)

First, compute each term:

\displaystyle \frac{1^2}{(2 \times 10^{-9})^2} = \frac{1}{4 \times 10^{-18}} = 2.5 \times 10^{17}

\displaystyle \frac{2^2}{(1 \times 10^{-9})^2} = \frac{4}{1 \times 10^{-18}} = 4.0 \times 10^{18}

So,\left( \frac{1^2}{(2 \times 10^{-9})^2} + \frac{2^2}{(1 \times 10^{-9})^2} \right)
= 2.5 \times 10^{17} + 4.0 \times 10^{18}
= 4.25 \times 10^{18}

Now calculate the prefactor:\frac{h^2}{8m} = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34})^2}{8 \times 9.109 \times 10^{-31}}
= \frac{4.39 \times 10^{-67}}{7.287 \times 10^{-30}}
\approx 6.02 \times 10^{-38}

Therefore,E_{1,2} \approx (6.02 \times 10^{-38})(4.25 \times 10^{18})
= 2.56 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J}

Convert to electronvolts:E_{1,2} = \frac{2.56 \times 10^{-19}}{1.602 \times 10^{-19}} \approx 1.60 \, \text{eV}

The energy of the electron in the 2D box for n_x = 1 and n_y = 2 is:E_{1,2} \approx 2.56 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \quad \text{or} \quad 1.60 \, \text{eV}.

